94th Street north from Ditmars Boulevard to Nineteenth Avenue. The creek in the foreground is known as Jackson's Mill Pond. He operated a grext mill here in the middle of the 19th century. According to J. Riker Jr's. map of 1852 of Newton, the one story building seen at the right is probably near or on the site of the mill. The road extending to the left beyond the creek is Old Bowery Road. The foundation for the mill was laid by Peter C. Luyster in 1668. The house in the background of view No. three, looking south, is that of
Abraham Rapelye in 1852.

94th Street (left), south from above Ditmars Boulevard, showing, on high ground, the two Rapelye houses and barns (right). In the foreground is Jackson Mill Creek and the land is part of the Rapelye farm. 94th Street is the former Old Bowery Road. Ditmars Avenue was later cut through just below the creek and Grand Central Parkway in the immediate foreground.

94th Street, east side, south of Ditmars Boulevard, showing in four views the J. I. Rapelye farmhouse of 1852. View one shows partially the above mentioned street which was originally known as Old Bowery Road. This house was demolished in May 1929. In 1908 it stood directly in the center of 95th Street (old 38th Street) about 208 ft. south of Ditmars Boulevard. This house faces north and was owned by A. Rapelye, 1860; C. P. Harris, 1873-1891; and C. H. Harris in 1896. Across Jackson Mill Pond on the east side of 94th Street, north of this house was located the T. B. Jackson house and mill. Samuel Fish, son of Nathan Fish became the owner in 1715. In 1724 he purchased the adjoining mill from the heirs of Jesse Kip. His son John (1719-1793) succeeded to the paternal estate and mill at Fish Point. His daughters Anna (b 1748) and Sarah (b 1762) married Jacob and William Palmer respectively. Their brother Samuel (b 1752- d 1834), a bachelor, owned the paternal estate.

Views 2&3: March 1925
View 4: March 1923
View 1: May 1926.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

94th Street, south from above Ditmars Boulevard, showing the Rapelye houses (right) and the C. P. Harris House (left). In the foreground is the Jackson Mill Creek and the bridge about 50 feet north of where Ditmars Boulevard was later cut through. Grand Central Parkway now (1940) traverses this foreground area from left to right. 94th Street, here, is the former Old Bowery Road.
